106

cation  as  important  as  the  ‘‘science’’  and  ‘‘math’’  in  all  policy-making,  funding,  K–
12 standards and curricula, teacher professional development and certification, and
student  programs  and  assessments.  NASA  is  uniquely  positioned  to  champion  the
technology  and  engineering  components  of  STEM,  inspiring  children  to  pursue  ca-
reers  in  these  areas.  NASA  can  focus  more  of  its  grant  activity  on  the  technology
and  engineering  curriculum,  teacher  professional  development,  and  support  the  de-
velopment  of  informal  science  education  programs,  such  as  museum  exhibits  and
television  programs.  NASA  can  again  become  the  main  driver  for  STEM  education
as it was after Sputnik.

As  you  pursue  education  and  innovation  policies  and  legislation,  please  also  con-

